description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/transport/ble_ipsp_transport.c
Lines: 106-111

In connected_cb(), when a connection is rejected because one already exists:

    if (transport_state.conn != NULL) {
        LOG_WRN("Already have connection, rejecting new one");
        k_mutex_unlock(&transport_state.lock);
        bt_conn_disconnect(conn, BT_HCI_ERR_REMOTE_USER_TERM_CONN);
        return;
    }

    transport_state.conn = bt_conn_ref(conn);  // Ref taken here

The bt_conn_ref() increments the reference count. If the connection establishment fails after this point, we rely on disconnected_cb() to call bt_conn_unref().

However, if bt_enable() or other BLE operations fail during init (lines 362-365), or if the transport is deinitialized while a connection exists, the reference may not be properly released.

In lichen_ble_transport_stop():
    if (transport_state.conn) {
        bt_conn_disconnect(transport_state.conn, ...);
    }

This triggers a disconnect but doesn't unref. The unref happens in disconnected_cb(), but if the callback doesn't fire (e.g., BLE stack shutdown), we leak the reference.

Fix: In lichen_ble_transport_stop(), also call bt_conn_unref() after disconnect, or ensure the reference is cleaned up in deinit.
